The first virtual provider comes to the Czech Republic already this year.
Maybe.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite mature, the Czech suppliers offer virtually all services, as they are offered by their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, there is something lacking here - a virtual provider who makes the classics at lower prices.
Maybe he won't be waiting for him for long.
The fact that the Czech mobile providers work on the most expensive in Europe at all, we have often reported on mobile.cz.
This also confirmed by the Telecommunications Authority ČTÚ, which pointed out that the price for a SMS here is higher than in the rest of the European Union.
Following the latest steps taken by the European Commission in the field of roaming fees, there is so likely a paradoxical situation - for some customers of the Czech mobile providers, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
Why are prices in the Czech Republic so high compared with Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that really makes a fight.
Perhaps it sounds paradoxical, because in the Czech Republic there are three mobile networks and a pénétration of far more than 100%.
On the other hand, mobile operators are happy to shy on the fact that there is extremely much competition on the Czech market.
The President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (ČTÚ) also often agrees to this, Pavel Dvo.k, who had often stated in the past that there was no room for another provider in the Czech Republic.
It is probably true that a classic provider with its own network no longer has so many opportunities (almost he would probably not find any more frequencies).
But there is another option - a virtual provider.
The entry of virtual operators into the mobile market led to a significant price reduction, which then also had to respond to by the classic mobile operators.
There were similar votes in the UK to those in the Czech Republic before such companies as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the market.
However, it has proved that there is room for such providers and that these can really be successful.
By the way, you don't have to look for examples long.
In February, we reported on the launch of the virtual provider Mobilking in Poland.
In just six months, this provider managed to win more than 100 thousand customers and thus climb to the five largest provider of the country.
The financial group Penta, which owns U:fon in the Czech Republic, is behind Mobilking.
The advantage of virtual providers is that one can concentrate on a much more concrete target group.
In order to function effectively, virtual providers need much less customers than a classic provider.
They do not need relatively high costs for the construction, operation and maintenance of a mobile network.
In the world, virtual providers usually look out as low-cost companies - they offer cheap phone calls and SMS, which is often accompanied by a less extensive offer of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half cheaper than its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it may also be quite a good move to put on a non-crystle target group.
This provider is specifically targeted at men.
"Good guys choose Mobilking - the provider they like and can trust," said David Seibert, CEO of the Mobile Entertainment Company, the operator of this virtual provider.
It is difficult to say whether a similar approach as in Poland could be taken in the Czech Republic.
The press speaker of Vodafone Miroslav Čepický also doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual providers are based.
It is also relatively saturated from the point of view of the provision of services."
In the Czech Republic chancelessly, mobile operators mean
But it is almost certain that when a virtual mobile provider conquers Czech Republic, this will not be mobile.
"While we talk about an expansion of this successful project, the negotiations in the Czech Republic do not look particularly hopeful.
The market entry of Mobilking in other countries of our region is more likely," says Mobil.cz Jana Studničková, a press speaker of the financial group Penta in a telephone interview.
Indirectly, it confirmed that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic are not particularly inclined to this idea.
On the contrary, they are trying to do everything they can to ensure that no potential competitor is created.
Their interest in the launch of a virtual mobile provider has long been showing the Group GTS Novera, who wants to take a further step to become a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the area of business customers.
"We have a great interest in offering our customers not only fixed network, but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the earlier, the better.
We have negotiated on this possibility with all Czech mobile providers on a number of occasions.
With some of them we have already been able to achieve negotiations," said the press spokesman of the Pavel Kaidl group.
Maybe better times are coming now.
Non-official information shows that the first virtual provider may be expected by the end of the year.
But so far this is surrounded by an insurmountable wall of silence.
"At this moment, we do not assume that in the Czech Republic there is room for a full virtual provider.
The Czech market is very specific to other markets.
To date, no subject has addressed us with a complex and serious project in this area," says in his statement for Mobil.cz Vlastimil Srše. from the press department of Telefónica O2.
Further suppliers also point to the specificity of the Czech market.
The press speaker of T-Mobile Martina Kemrová rarely adds to O2's statement: "We have not yet found a viable and both-sided project on which we could continue to build."
And she adds: "A virtual provider will hardly appear in the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
At this moment we would have to have a concrete offer already in place in order to be able to think so short-term."
Vodafone focuses its attention on meeting the requirements of its own 3G licence.
Miroslav Čepický says: "For negotiations with potential virtual providers, we are open, especially in the area of cost and infrastructure sharing.
This is precisely what we view as the best from the point of view of the customers.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to seek a partner to build a shared network for a fast mobile Internet."
The responsible authorities - with the suppliers hand in hand
The behaviour of mobile operators is easy to understand; another provider would be more competitive, this would lead to lower prices and thus to a decrease in profits.
So why should such a competitor be facilitated to enter the market?
The fact that the suppliers can draw a string when it comes to something also proves the long way and then about the emergence of U:fon.
At the time when U:fon came on the market, the strongest pressure in the direction of ČTÚ was due to the company T-Mobile.
This also proves the information available to the public from the ČTÚ websites.
Now, however, U:fon is right as an argument why you should not allow a virtual provider.
Martina Kemrová said: "The competitive field of the mobile market has recently also been strengthened by the entry into the market of a fourth mobile provider.
Taking into account the character of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is clear that a new player would have high demands on the market itself and, above all, its services."
In view of this approach of mobile operators, however, the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory authorities is amazed.
This is not just the position of the ČTÚ, which unfortunately, unlike the UK and other highly developed countries, does not have the competence to intervene in economic competition.
It owns exclusively the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
This, however, referred to the whole problem of its very typical attitude.
"The entry into the market of a virtual mobile provider would be possible after a contract has been concluded between a mobile provider and a virtual provider through the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
To date, no such agreement has been concluded, because the offer of potential stakeholders was probably not sufficiently interesting for the classic suppliers," says Kristián Chalupa in his answer to our question from the Department of External Relations of the ÚOHS.
Such a wording would not be surprised by representatives of the suppliers.
This is more than worrying by an authority representing the interests of consumers and, inter alia, ensuring that no one abuses his position on the market.
In particular, when Kristián Chalupa adds: "In abroad, where virtual providers work normally, it should be observed that their entry into the market has contributed to a price reduction in mobile telephone services."
However, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market and price reduction are probably not among the interests of the ÚOHS.
In this case, the almost already touching harmony of the three mobile operators, which results from their reactions, is really shocking.
The question of whether it really is just a coincidence is obvious.
Just like the absolutely equal petrol price at the petrol stations is certainly just a coincidence and the result of a hard competition.
"The Authority has not found any signs of any action against competition in this case, and therefore it has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the suppliers has a dominant market position, so they do not have the corresponding increased responsibility for their activities on the market.
The necessary tools for opening up the mobile market for virtual providers are probably also missing from the Telecommunications regulatory authority," Chalupa stated in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many controversial points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets, developed by the ČTÚ, according to which telecommunications is one single market from the point of view of economic competition.
On such a market, of course, none of the Czech mobile operators has a dominant position.
Some legal experts, however, offer a different viewpoint - for the entry into the market of a virtual provider, the consent of the network operator is always necessary.
And the mobile provider - logically - has monopoly for his network.
This means that he must take a dominant position in a particular segment.
However, even if you do not support this argument, it should at least be a warning for the ÚOHS that three mobile operators are acting noticeably similar.
Complaints from a number of interested parties (including the company GTS Novera mentioned) show that they encounter very similar obstacles in negotiations with all suppliers.
The waging of responsibility to the ČTÚ is then a quite common trick in the telecommunications services, with which the ÚOHS is distant from the whole matter.
This has already been observed in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, in the recent Novelle of the Telecommunications Act, the extension of ČTÚ's competences to the field of economic competition in telecommunications has not been achieved, although a number of experts had promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the ÚOHS must only know that too well, but probably they have other interests.
I'll be fine if no one watches
Notwithstanding this, the operation of any pseudovirtuous provider, of which there are just a few in the Czech mobile networks, remains.
They are companies that issue their own price lists for mobile telecommunications services, but they are only partially public.
Normally, they are companies operating in the field of multi-level marketing.
Private mobile telephone services offer, for example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others.
The price lists of these companies usually only come to selected companies.
The joke of the case is that the company appears to be a classic company customer in relation to the operator who orders a lot of SIM cards.
As an important customer he then receives special price offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit similar resale.
"If there are cases you describe, it may be a violation of the contractual conditions with which we will then deal with, which can lead to an end to cooperation with the relevant society," Martina Kemrová answered our question on this issue.
However, it is quite unlikely that something like this does not speak around with the mobile operators.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned, there may be thousands of customers.
However, no operator resists such an approach.
In fact, the activities of these companies do not result in negligible profits, at the same time, as opposed to actual virtual providers, they are not affected by the actual official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický draws attention to possible problems: "The law allows such speculations, despite all, the services of these companies are only used by a very small percentage of customers.
In addition, they must accept that the SIM card does not run on their phone on their name, so they cannot fully possess the normal customers of mobile operators."
This alone, however, would have to happen to the ČTÚ at least strangely.
Furthermore, another question arises for the ÚOHS.
Mobile operators close their eyes in front of such an approach, why are they blocking themselves against a virtual provider?
It should be added that the ÚOHS has quite strong competences to detect such activities, and if it does not want it does not have to satisfy itself with the supplier's statement that they would not know anything about it and their terms of business would prohibit it.
When the Czech Republic is no longer the most expensive
As has already been emphasised several times in the text, the entry into the market of virtual providers led to a significant price decline in the various services.
In practical terms, in all countries where virtual providers have emerged, classic suppliers have tried to prevent their formation practically more or less.
The arguments they used were practically identical - a too small, or too saturated market, problems in the quality of services, etc.
In the highly developed countries, however, the regulatory bodies, which tried not to safeguard the interests of mobile operators, but of their customers, were involved in these moments.
Whether it was through formal measures or non-formal pressure, they reached that the first virtual operator was created, and this followed further.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory bodies are thrown up all the case like a hot potato.
Based on our experience, we cannot lose the impression that ambiguity in the competences in these cases is more than favourable.
But we don't throw the flint into the grain.
If the background information is correct and a virtual provider will soon appear, the Czech mobile market may soon return.
If a provider permits the emergence of a virtual mobile provider, the ÚOHS will not remain inactive when it comes to rejecting (discriminating) other interested parties.
And then the Czechs will not finally call more expensive than the rest of Europe.
