Speech - The blood that became safe again
Hema-Quebec celebrated yesterday the 10th anniversary of its establishment, and her president, Dr. Francine Décary, had every reason to rejoice, because Hema-Quebec has become one of the safest and most efficient blood banks in the world.
And above all, it has recovered the public's confidence, which had been severely shaken by the scandal of contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As we know, the national blood reserves managed by the blood donor service of the Canadian Red Cross were infected with the HI virus and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In view of this drama and the discontent of the public, in February 1994, the Government of Canada initiated a public investigation, led by Judge Horace Krever, aimed at bringing light to the circumstances that had led to such a tragedy, and developing guidelines to prevent a new disaster of this kind.
While Judge Krever still hesitated to file his report, several provinces put a committee on their feet to develop a new system for the administration of blood conserves in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this mission.
According to the reports of Gélineau and Krever, two blood banks were established in Canada: Hema-Quebec, responsible for Quebec, and the Canadian blood society to provide the other provinces and the two territories.
`1998, when Hema-Quebec started working, barely 38% of people had confidence in the blood conservation system in Quebec, remembers Dr. Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
By the enormous efforts to improve the safety of blood conserves and by working in this area over the next few years, we have recovered public confidence," she proudly stresses that at the beginning of 2008, almost 94% of Quebec's population had confidence in Hema-Quebec.
Dr. Décary, however, keeps in mind that 'trust is something extremely fragile'.
Since its establishment on 28 September 1998, Hema-Quebec has acted in accordance with the principle of caution.
At that time, we experienced numerous cases of human form of bovine madness in Europe, a new type of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, this woman, who has been in charge since its founding in 1998.
`And we did not have the least idea if this disease could be transmitted through the blood.
So we are referring to one of the main guidelines of the Krever and Gélineau reports, which states that exclusion measures are applied if you do not know this and if a disease only progresses slowly, as is apparently the case with Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is expressed by a degeneration of the brain, which inevitably leads to death.
So in April 1999, no blood was taken from people who had been in the United Kingdom since 1980 for more than a month.
Well, a few years ago, without any doubt, this disease was proven to be transmitted through the blood.
So this event has shown us that the principle of precaution that we applied has quite a sense.
In 1999, a much more precise technique for the detection of HIV appeared on the market: the nucleic acid tests (NSTs) which allow to demonstrate the presence of the virus itself directly in the blood of the donor, and not the antibodies against the virus, as was the case with the tests previously used.
The NST enabled the incubation time to be shortened between the time when the person was infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected by our techniques in the blood, the specialist explains.
This time could be reduced to a duration of less than one week.
Thus, the risk that some donors could be infected without knowing and could not be recognized has been significantly reduced.
These improvements made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of transmission of AIDS through blood transfusion.
Today, one out of 12 million people is at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
`In other words, this means that you need to distribute 12 million blood containers before someone gets infected with HIV.
Since Hema-Quebec is distributed between 400,000 and 500,000 blood containers each year, it would take more than 24 years before a case occurs in which HIV was transmitted via a blood container.
I believe that you can feel comfortable today when you get a blood transfusion or prescribe to restore your health," says the head of management of Hema-Quebec.
`Our challenge for the next ten years is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which disease agent can get into the system.
Only last year has the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the Westnil virus, is transmitted by insects through the blood.
We have to keep on monitoring', Dr. Décary continues before she stresses that Hema-Quebec must also provide adequate care in addition to a secure supply.
`The need increases because the population ages.
Since cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need new red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also affects the blood donor network, with an average of only 3% of Quebec's residents suitable for blood donation.
Any healthy person who is 18 years old or older and meets the criteria can give blood every 56 days, i.e. six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who make their blood available are not accepted because, for example, they are suffering from AIDS or malaria, and whoever has travelled to a country where malaria is widespread is excluded from blood donation for one year.
`With these 3% we manage to obtain an inventory that meets the needs of the hospitals.
Deficiency in stocks is very rare.
But you have to renew the members of this donor network when they get older and can no longer give blood.
It is difficult to convince people to give blood, but above all to keep them and to make them become regular donors.
Life is so hectic today that one rarely finds time to spend an hour on blood donating," says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Quebec delivers not only blood conserves, but also human tissues, including bone transplantations, heartfelts, eye apples and skin, which is used almost exclusively for severe fire injuries.
These tissues are examined, processed and frozen before they are intermediately stored at Hema-Quebec, which also manages the only public nabel cord blood bank in Quebec.
In the navel cord, which was previously considered to be biomedical waste, stem cells have rich blood that can serve to treat serious diseases such as leukemia.
`A few weeks ago we celebrated the deposit of our 1,000th nail cord blood sample, and we are planning to lose more than 1,000 per year.
‘We should probably start making it available for transplantations at the beginning of next year’, says Dr. Décary, who describes this program of navel cord blood loss as very popular.
‘Many mothers are convinced that they have no access to it’, because Hema-Quebec lacks the means to offer this complex and expensive program in all Quebec hospitals.
