The psychology of overflowing - or why we are willing to pay more
In the case of auctions, the buyers tend to spend more and thus overestimate the bidder.
Neurologists and economic researchers at the University of New York have now managed to discover the neurological-economic foundations of this known and apparently irrational behaviour.
According to a study published in the "Science" magazine, people do not want to be beaten in a competition, such as an auction on eBay, and are therefore willing to pay even excessive prices.
The researchers have tried to explore the neurological scheme of this "game" with experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers should play lottery while the other took part in a playful action - in both cases the active brain regions of the subjects were investigated using functional magnetic resonance (fMRI).
In both games the participants were able to win money, but an increased activity of the striatum, a complex below the brain, was measured in losers of the auction, in which the overflow of the opponent plays an important role.
In addition to many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the "self reward" of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore argued that the price increase could be explained by avoiding a overreaction of the striatum.
In order to support their thesis, economists in the research group have also carried out investigations to track the money.
In this case, three groups should be involved against a partner under different conditions.
The control group was informed of the true value of the product, and then they made their efforts.
Another group was also promised $15 reward in case they emerged as winners of the game.
The third group received 15 dollars before the auction, which were also lost in case of a lost game.
So the difference between the two groups was only that the emphasis was on the one on the profit, the other was on the loss.
However, as proof of the hypothesis expressed by neurologues, the members of the "game against losing" group were prepared to make a higher stake than those in the control or "winning" group.
"These results can be derived from no previous economic theory.
These have, in fact, only motivated the behaviour observed at auctions with the joy of gaining, or risk avoidance.
The contradiction between these two theories has been resolved thanks to the visual neurological processes, so we have now a third statement prepared" - Andrew Schotter, Professor of Economic Faculty at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When should the doctor be consulted?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed among the leading causes of death.
The number of infected is estimated to be a hundred thousand, but only seven thousand are treated, because patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective term for liver disease caused by various viruses.
The symptoms are often similar - liver inflammation and yellowishness are common, but the pathogens and diseases differ from each other.
Depending on the pathogens, hepatitis viruses are spread in two different ways: in hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (e.g. through contaminated food or water), in hepatitis B, C and D, the viruses can be transmitted through blood and other body fluids (e.g. sperm, secrecy or spice).
Travellers are recommended to vaccinate against viruses A and B in any case, and there is no vaccine against virus C.
The symptoms of hepatitis A show approximately two-three weeks after consumption of the contaminated food and are generally accompanied by malaise, weakness, abdominal pain and fracture.
Afterwards the yellowing occurs on the skin and in the eyes, the chair becomes bright, the urine dark, and the healing can take up to two-three weeks.
Worldwide, around 1 million people die each year of the much more severe diseases caused by hepatitis B, such as liver cancer and liver cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only every tenth of the infected is in medical treatment.
Hepatitis C may also have serious consequences: untreated it can lead to liver cirrhosis and liver cancer.
Most infected people don't even know about their disease because the pathogen destroys the liver cells intuitively - in many cases the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, such as regular checks, is essential.
There are three groups in which this disease is more common: those who were subjected to blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattoos.
Currently, the number of chronic hepatitis C patients worldwide is estimated to be 200 million.
Since the disease is already detectable during a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to visit the doctor at the first signs of unknown origin.
At the right time, the disease is healable, the virus can be eradicated, thereby eliminating the risk of infection and preventing the development of cancer.
September 30th, the World Day of Hepatitis, was held for the first time by patient representations worldwide in 2004.
The aim of the action is to strengthen awareness of this chronic liver inflammation caused by viruses, their formation and the importance of early detection.
