As the latest research results show, religious faith acts like a kind of "painful agent" that should have already facilitated the death of Catholic martyrs.
Scientists at Oxford University have carried out an interesting experiment: It has been investigated to what extent faith in God influences the feeling of human pain, reported the British paper "Telegraph".
In the course of the rather bizarre study, each 12 believers and atheists received electroshocks while studying a painting of the Mother of God.
As the results showed, the believers were able to eliminate most of the pain.
Through a brain scan technology, it has even been demonstrated that the Catholics have been able to activate the part of their brain that is responsible for pain control.
The study was the first in a research project in which philosophers and theologists from various departments of the university also participated in the research project.
In the trial, a sparkling device was connected to the left hand to the subjects, which gave the electro shocks.
The participants were asked to focus strongly on two paintings: On the one hand a picture of the Mother of God, painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century, and on the other Leonardo da Vinci's "Dame with the Hermelin".
The researchers hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary among the believers would create a kind of religious trance while selecting Vinci's image because it was hardly different from the other painting and felt as calming.
The subjects spent half an hour in a MRI scanner, and received a total of 20 electric shocks in four stages during that time, while they should either look at the religious, or the other painting.
The Catholics reported that when they looked at God's Mother, they felt "in security" as if they were "cared" and they felt "rest and peace".
While viewing the religious painting, they reported 12% less pain than when they had Leonardo's work in mind.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who also took part in the attempt, said that one could also produce similar effects with other, highly active images also among the atheists, just to find the appropriate photo.
"We need to find a picture that causes very positive feelings like a mother or a father," said the psychologist.
Anglican bishop Tom Wright welcomed the results of the research.
"The practice of faith should change our personality, and does it in many cases," Wright said.
After these excellent results, only the question remains what effect a Madonna image Leonardos or another similar painter would have on the pain regulation of the believers.
Would the high-quality Virgin Mary achieve even better results?
