What would be the best method for developing new technologies to avoid accidents if not to imitate the barrier sensors from nature?
For example, those of the bees.
The CEATEC in Japan presented an amazing project that inspired the Nissan engineers of Hummeln in creating new systems to prevent accidents.
In cooperation with the Tokyo University, Nissan has built the BR23C-type biomimetic system controlled by authoroboters, a mini car equipped with the properties of bees, with the aim of supporting the development of a system that avoids any collision.
On the flight, each bee forms its own oval "private area", which is very similar to our own "shield", said Kazuhhiro Doi, product manager for technology PR and research development, at the exhibition.
The composite eye of the bee, which can see in every direction and in an angle of more than 300 degrees, plays an important role.
In order to imitate the function of the composite eye, the researchers took the idea of the laser-controlled distance meter.
This identifies obstacles to the BR23C in a 180-degree face field within 2 meters, calculates their distances and sends signals to the microprocessor to Board, which immediately launches the anti-collision process.
The obstacle is recorded in second break parts, and the authoroboter immediately changes the course, similar to the movement of the bees by turning the tyres around the appropriate angle.
Contrary to previous systems, this manoeuvre takes place purely instinctively.
"If not, the authorobot could not react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," said Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the "Mobility Laboratory" and the authoroboter project.
The system must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the innerst and most vulnerable part of the shield - a layer that is currently considered inevitable within the accident.
The whole process must reflect the behaviour of the bees when they avoid other bees.
And that must happen in the fraction of a second.
However, the evasion, unlike the bees, can not go up, down, or even diagonally - it can only be two-dimensional, only towards the turnability of the tyres.
While the bees here are infinitely open to avoid other bees, the researchers at the authoroboter could only use the rotational movement, or the acceleration and brake.
The BR23C contains lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and more energy-efficient and therefore have a longer lifetime than conventional lithium ion batteries.
Andoh explained that it is important to the instinctive, intelligent response, and less to the processing of the data, and even less to the ability to store them.
This device must only process some inputs per second and respond accordingly.
It does not need to store it, or by using previous manoeuvres, to produce an intuitive, logical reaction, so it is constantly using only a handful of KB Memory.
There is no need for gigabyte and megabyte heavy memories.
This is the first step in the development of the immediate anti-collision technology, which, according to Nissan's assessment, will be in production in the next ten years.
Another application could find the technology in GPS satellite navigation by consciously guiding the driver around obstacles and thus leading him to the target.
