The figures provided by Anec, the central trade association, speak a clear language: in the last five years the enormous amount of 316 traditional cinemas have had to close; this book largely paid the cinemas in the major cities: 10 in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
Among the most affected regions are Emilia-Romagna with 82 lost cinemas, followed by Tuscany with 44 and Lombardy with 41.
This proves that the main guilty are the multiplex cinemas, because it is just these three regions in which the largest number of these modern cinemas has been registered: with 195 in the last 5 years the Lombardy has put on the lists, 81 in both Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
"The business has evolved in an irrational way," says Paolo Protti, President of the Anec, "it is useful that new structures are also created, but first of all, the preservation of the already existing, because closes a hall in the city, not all of his parent customers are willing to visit instead of the old multiplex cinema in the periphery.
And here is the lack of budget for the trade union fund: the debt burden recorded by the state is about EUR 10 million.
It is a shame of the ethical-moral view that the government does not respect existing laws.
In order to preserve the sector, between 16 and 18 million euros per year would be needed."
Interestingly, the case of Bologna, the first Italian city, which, due to the fears of the old cinema halls, has decided to protect them by an agreement between the municipality and the Anec; it is the first agreement of this kind in Italy to protect and support traditional cinemas, both in the historical centre and in the periphery.
Among the measures envisaged are also tax concessions for cinema operators and benefits for the public in relation to transport: it will be possible to drive into the traffic-limited areas of the centre and to park at more affordable parking charges.
"It's a joyful initiative," says Giuseppe Tornatore, "I hope that other cities will join us and develop new concepts.
Certainly, however, we also need better audio and video equipment to be able to counter the superpower of the multiplex halls, because the audience of today is more demanding.
The defence of the traditional cinema has always been an important subject for me: the closure of the "Supercinema" of Baghiera, the place of my childhood and youth, was the decisive point that led me to set up the "Nuovo cinema Paradiso", even though I had been playing with the thought for 10 years.
For 25 years I have lived in Rome; when I pass at the Rialto or the Quirinal in the Via Nazional, where I have experienced so many different emotions, I turn to the side to avoid having to see the dust-covered posters.
