When the energy comes out of the waves, the big ones suddenly run up
It is a non-sweeping source of money that covers over 70% of the surface of the planet and only now seems to understand this to the great energy companies in the world.
Wells, currents and tides are the new renewable energy sources that are now all looking at, and also looking for opacity, such as giants like Chevron.
The possibility of gaining energy from the movements of the sea has been considered and investigated for 70 years; not randomly, these studies have intensified considerably since the first oil crisis.
When the price of oil broke in 1980, the idea of marine energy was gasped, but now the environmental organisations and the rise in oil prices are pushing for new impulses in this sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimates that 15% of the global energy demand could be covered by the energy generated by ocean waves.
This would be equal to the double of the current energy produced by nuclear power plants.
The currents and tides would also be added.
Giant at the attack.
The first company now relying on marine energy is Enersis, which signed a contract for the construction of a power plant in northern Portugal in 2005.
When this message was published it seemed to be a revolutionary step.
Two years later, there are more and more companies from the traditional energy industry who are relying on marine energy generation.
"Chevron is studying these technologies" – according to the speaker of a company known to the American giant in the Wall Street Journal – and considering the possibility of working with us."
This is about the acquisition of an approval from the American Energy Commission, which is necessary to launch a project in front of Alaska's coast.
This is a sign not to be underestimated, i.e. when you consider that oil continues to be promoted by the US in Alaska and President Bush has recently launched plans for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, the companies Verdant Power Inc. from New York and Ocean Power from New Jersey are also investing in the new industry; the details are also unknown, so observers speak of an increasing interest.
